Following plans by the Ondo State Government to reduce unemployment to the barest minimum, Governor Oluwarotimi Akeredolu-led government has partnered with Small and Medium Enterprises Development Agency of Nigeria (SMEDAN) and the Central Bank of Nigeria (CBN) to empower over 360 youths on different business enterprise. Governor Oluwarotimi Akeredolu unveiled this yesterday at a three-day entrepreneurship programme, organised by the Ministry of Youths and Sports Development in collaboration with SMEDAN, which would end tomorrow. According to Akeredolu, one of the major problems facing youths in the country was unemployment, hence the need to train youths on businesses became inevitable. The governor, who was represented by his Deputy, Hon Agboola Ajayi, said one of the core values of his cardinal action plan as a government was human capital development, being the foundation of socio-economic growth of the state. Akeredolu said: “As our administration is committed to sustainable youth empowerment, this three-day capacity building training is intended to unlock and re-invent your creative potential and provide another opportunity for you to either start or scale up your existing businesses. “We cannot pretend to be unaware of the teething challenges confronting up and coming young entrepreneurs, notably the inability to access the initial capital outlay.” Also, Commissioner for Youth and Sport Development, Mr. Dotun Owanikin said the programme showed the commitment of the governor towards youths in the state as the training would make the youths self-reliant and empowering them to ensuring a sustainable employment opportunities in the state. Owanikin revealed that each local government had minimum of 20 youths, saying “what we are trying to do here is to start a chain of employment for the youths in the state.”